SVG Fill

The fill property of <svg> elements can be styled with css, just like background/color properties.

The fill class can be applied directly to a <path>, or to the parent <svg> element to fill all its children's <path>s. Which colours are available depends on the colours module, and any customisation that has been applied.

.fill-x

.fill-wht

.fill-white

.fill-cream

.fill-light

.fill-grey

.fill-dark

.fill-pitch

.fill-black

.fill-blk

.fill-pink

.fill-violet

.fill-purple

.fill-blue

.fill-mint

SVGs designed by freepik

Usage example

<svg class="fill-red">
  <path> <!-- svg path is red --> </path>
  <path> <!-- svg path is red --> </path>
  <path class="fill-purple"> <!-- svg path is red --> </path>
  <path class="fill-teal"> <!-- svg path is teal --> </path>
</svg>

Media Queries

No media query support for this property. It might not be necessary to supply different values at different breakpoints. Please refer to (the media-query documentation) for more info.

Customising

Default Classes

The fill colours are prefixed with fill- by default, but this can be changed with the $svg-fill-prop variable.

// change the class prefix to .svg-
$svg-fill-prop: "svg";

Custom Background Colours

As with all colours, the fill property inherits the default $colors map. You may customise the colours used for fills by supplying a $svg-fill-colors map instead.

// change the fill colours to only gun-metal and black.
$svg-fill-colors: (
  gun-metal: #45494a,
  black: #000
);

Combined

After changing the prefix property and the map of colours in the previous two customisations, we would end up with the following css.

/* would result in css like: */
.svg-gun-metal  { fill: #45494a; }
.svg-black      { fill: #000; }

view the source on github: /src/components/svg/_fill.scss
